=== TASK ===
# Audit List / Site Manager

## Overview
Develop a feature-rich Audit List / Site Manager page for the OfficeInventory AI platform. This page presents audits organized hierarchically by tenant → site → floor/zone, enables creating new audits, cloning existing audits, and navigating into site/floor details. The UI emphasizes a clear hierarchical tree, audit summary cards, bulk actions with proper permission checks, and an intuitive flow for selecting sites/floors when creating audits. Everything must be built with runtime safety in mind: guards against null/undefined, proper default initializations, and robust input validation.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A centralized Audit List / Site Manager interface that displays audits organized by tenant, site, and floor/zone in a hierarchical, expandable tree. It also shows a gallery/list of audit cards for quick scanning and management.

Goals:
- Provide an at-a-glance overview of audits across tenants and sites.
- Allow users to create new audits via a Create Audit modal, selecting tenant/site/floor, audit name, schedule, and assigned team.
- Allow cloning an existing audit to duplicate configuration and tasks into a new audit.
- Enable navigation into site and floor details to view deeper metadata, items detected, status, and review queues.
- Support bulk actions (Export, Archive, Delete) with permission checks and audit-logging.

UI elements and how they should look:
- Hierarchy Tree: A collapsible tree showing Tenant > Site > Floor/Zone. Each node can be expanded/crolled, with inline action pills (e.g., View, Clone, Add Audit).
- Audit Cards: Cards displaying audit title, status, item count, last updated, owner, and quick action icons (Open, Clone, Export).
- Create Audit Modal: A modal form to create a new audit by selecting Tenant → Site → Floor/Zone, entering an audit name, choosing a schedule (date/time or recurrence), and assigning a team.
- Bulk Actions Bar: A toolbar enabling Export, Archive, and Delete actions with user permissions checks and progress indicators.
- Detail Navigation: Clicking a site/floor in the tree navigates to a detail panel or page showing items, AI-detected inventory, review queues, and activity logs.

Visual guidance:
- Layout emphasizes whitespace, card-based surfaces, and a left-hand navigation/branching tree with edge-to-edge cards for audit lists.
- Use the provided color palette, typography, and spacing guidelines to ensure consistency with the enterprise design system.
- Maintain high contrast for key actions (accent green) and strong anchors (black surfaces for navigation/summary panels).

APIs connected:
- No APIs connected in the current brief; the page should be designed to integrate with REST or GraphQL endpoints for tenants, sites, floors, audits, and audit items. Prepare data shapes and placeholders for future API wiring.

PROJECT CONTEXT RELEVANCE:
- This page is part of OfficeInventory AI – Enterprise Furniture Audit Platform. It must align with the platform’s architecture: tenant isolation, role-based access, audit logs, and scalable data models for audits, items, locations, and review decisions. The UI should support an audit lifecycle from creation through review and reporting, with a future path for 2D space planning and ESG reporting.

---

## Components to Build

1) HierarchyTree
- Purpose: Render hierarchical Tenant → Site → Floor/Zone with expand/collapse behavior.
- Data shape assumptions:
  - tenants: Array<Tenant>, where Tenant has id, name, sites: Array<Site>
  - Site has id, name, floors: Array<Floor>, tenantId
  - Floor has id, name, zones: Array<Zone>, siteId
  - Zone has id, name, floorId
- Features:
  - Expand/collapse nodes; preserve expanded state in local UI state.
  - Inline actions per node (View Site, View Floor, Create Audit under a specific node).
  - Guard against null/undefined at every level; use data ?? [] with Array.isArray checks.
- UI elements: Tree nodes with indent, chevrons, and small pill actions.

2) AuditCard
- Purpose: Display a summarized view of an audit.
- Data shape: Audit { id, name, status, itemCount, lastUpdated, owner, siteId, floorId, zoneId, tenantId, ... }
- Visuals: Title, status badge, item count, lastUpdated, owner avatar/name, small tags for zone/site.
- Interactions: Open (navigate to audit detail), Clone (duplicate audit), Export (download CSV), select (for bulk actions).
- Safety: Always guard array-derived values; treat missing counts as 0 using (audit?.itemCount ?? 0).

3) CreateAuditModal
- Purpose: Gather inputs to create a new audit with hierarchical location selection.
- Fields:
  - Tenant: select
  - Site: select (filtered by tenant)
  - Floor/Zone: select (filtered by site/floor)
  - Audit Name: text input
  - Schedule: date/time or recurring options
  - Assigned Team: multi-select or single select
- Validation: required on tenant, site, floor/zone, audit name; schedule must be valid; teams must be non-empty if required.
- Interactions: Debounced search for tenants/sites if dataset is large; disable submit if invalid.
- Safety: Normalize inputs; ensure defaults (empty arrays) where needed.

4) BulkActionsBar
- Purpose: Provide bulk operations: Export, Archive, Delete with permission checks.
- Behavior: Enable when one or more audits are selected; show loading/progress states; confirm destructive actions.
- Safety: Guard against null selections; ensure operations operate on arrays via (selection ?? []).map(...).

5) SiteDetailPanel (or RouteProxy)
- Purpose: Navigate into site/floor details; shows deeper metadata, inventory items, and review queues.
- Data shape: SiteDetail { id, name, floors, audits, items, queues, activityLog } with proper guards.
- Interactions: Navigate from tree or audit card; fetch related data (guarded by safety patterns).

6) ActivityLogPanel
- Optional: Show recent actions on an audit or site for audit traceability.

7) toast/notification system
- For success/failure messages of create/clone/export actions.

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Framework on offer should be React (with TypeScript preferred).
- State management: Use React hooks; maintain local UI state for tree expansion, selection, modal visibility, and audit filters.
- Routing: Use a router (e.g., React Router) to navigate to audit detail and site/floor detail pages.
- Data handling patterns:
  - All API responses must be validated: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
  - Supabase-like results should use data ?? [] for lists (if integrated later).
  - Guard all array operations: (items ?? []).map(...), Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
- Components should be accessible: keyboard navigation for tree, ARIA labels for controls.
- Accessibility: Ensure color contrast follows WCAG, provide alt text for icons, and meaningful focus states.
- Styling: Implement according to Visual Style section, using the provided color palette, typography, spacing, and card patterns.
- Performance: Lazy load sections of the tree as users expand; virtualization not required for MVP but consider due to potentially large tenant/site trees.
- Testing: Add unit tests for data guards (null/undefined), tree expansion logic, and modal validation.

### Backend
- APIs (to be wired later) should expose:
  - GET /tenants with nested sites and floors (or separate endpoints to each level)
  - GET /audits filtered by tenant/site/floor
  - POST /audits to create a new audit
  - POST /audits/{id}/clone to duplicate an audit
  - POST /audits/bulk-export
  - POST /audits/bulk-archive
  - DELETE /audits/bulk-delete
  - GET /sites/{id} and GET /sites/{id}/floors for detail view
- Data models (to be supported in future wiring):
  - Tenant, Site, Floor, Zone
  - Audit: id, name, status, ownerId, tenantId, siteId, floorId, zoneId, itemCount, lastUpdated
  - AuditItem: id, type, attributes, confidence, evidenceUrl, location
  - ActivityLog: id, auditId, action, timestamp, userId
- Security: Ensure endpoints accommodate role-based access; support placeholder for SSO and RBAC.

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - HierarchyTree fetches tenants/sites/floors data.
  - AuditCard consumes audits filtered by the selected location in the tree or top-level view.
  - CreateAuditModal feeds into POST /audits to create a new audit; upon success, refresh the relevant list and tree state.
  - Clone action uses POST /audits/{id}/clone and refreshes the list with new audit data.
  - BulkActionsBar dispatches to bulk endpoints and updates UI accordingly.
  - SiteDetailPanel fetches deeper site/floor data when navigating from the tree or card interactions.
- Data safety: All mapping and rendering should use safe guards like (data ?? []) and Array.isArray checks to prevent runtime errors.

---

## User Experience Flow

1) Landing on Audit List / Site Manager
- User sees a hierarchical tree on the left (Tenant → Site → Floor/Zone).
- On the right, a grid/list of AuditCards reflecting audits in the selected location (or all audits if none selected).
- Bulk actions bar is visible when one or more audits are selected.

2) Exploring the Hierarchy
- User expands a Tenant to reveal Sites, then Floors/Zones.
- Clicking a Site or Floor adjusts the audit grid to show audits under that scope.
- Hovering a card reveals quick actions (Open, Clone, Export).

3) Creating a New Audit
- User clicks Create Audit button.
- CreateAuditModal appears. User selects Tenant → Site → Floor/Zone, enters Audit Name, selects Schedule, assigns Team.
- Form validates; on success, API call is made to create audit; UI shows loading state and then refreshes audit list and tree.
- After creation, user can open the new audit from the grid or navigate to its detail.

4) Cloning an Audit
- User clicks Clone on an AuditCard.
- A new audit record is created copying configuration and tasks; UI shows success toast and updates the grid with the new audit.

5) Bulk Actions
- User selects multiple audits; BulkActionsBar activates.
- User chooses Export/Archive/Delete; confirmation prompt shows if destructive; upon confirmation, actions are executed and results reflected in UI.

6) Navigating into Site/Floor Details
- User clicks a Site or Floor in the tree; app navigates to a detailed view (SiteDetailPanel or dedicated route) showing location metadata, item inventory, review queues, and activity logs.

7) Feedback & Validation
- All forms provide inline validation; errors use the red/orange accents for visibility.
- Success messages appear via toasts with the lime green accent.

---

## Technical Specifications

Data Models
- Tenant: { id: string, name: string }
- Site: { id: string, name: string, tenantId: string }
- Floor: { id: string, name: string, siteId: string }
- Zone: { id: string, name: string, floorId: string }
- Audit: { id: string, name: string, status: string, itemCount: number, lastUpdated: string, ownerId: string, tenantId: string, siteId: string, floorId: string, zoneId: string, assignedTeamIds: string[] }
- AuditItem: { id: string, type: string, attributes: object, confidence: number, evidenceUrl: string, location: { x: number, y: number } }
- ActivityLog: { id: string, auditId: string, action: string, timestamp: string, userId: string }

API Endpoints (to be wired)
- GET /tenants?includeSites=true
- GET /tenants/{tenantId}/sites
- GET /sites/{siteId}/floors
- GET /audits?tenantId=&siteId=&floorId=&zoneId=
- POST /audits
- POST /audits/{auditId}/clone
- POST /audits/bulk-export
- POST /audits/bulk-archive
- DELETE /audits/bulk-delete
- GET /sites/{siteId}
- GET /sites/{siteId}/floors/{floorId}

Security
- Role-based access: read-only for restricted roles; create/clone/delete require appropriate permissions.
- SSO-ready bearer token validation placeholders; ensure endpoints will enforce tenant isolation.

Validation
- Client-side:
  - All forms use required fields; dates/times must be valid.
  - Use default values for arrays: audit.assignedTeamIds ?? [].
  - Guard all array operations: (array ?? []).map(...)
- Server-side (assumed):
  - Validate tenant/site/floor IDs exist and belong to the same tenant.
  - Validate audit name uniqueness within the scope.
  - Validate that bulk actions only affect audits the user can access.

Accessibility
- All interactive elements have ARIA labels.
- Keyboard navigation for tree and modals.
- High-contrast color states for status and actions.

Error Handling
- Graceful fallback to empty arrays when API returns null.
- Toast notifications for errors with actionable guidance.

